Explanation:

- The PATCH /admin/users/{user} route is handled by App\Http\Controllers\Admin\UserController::update(). The route is declared in routes/admin.php as a resource route for 'users' with update enabled, so the endpoint path parameter is {user}.
- The controller method signature is update(UsersRequest $request, User $user). The User is bound from the {user} path parameter â€” so there is a required path parameter named "user". The User model uses an integer primary key (id), so the path parameter type is integer.
- Validation rules are defined in app/Http/Requests/Admin/UsersRequest.php and apply to this request. Those rules indicate the expected body fields:
  - name: required, string, max:255, with a custom AlphaName rule (so only alphabetic/name-safe characters).
  - email: required, string in email format (unique rule applies but is not part of the parameter object structure).
  - password: nullable, confirmed (so a companion password_confirmation field is expected for confirmation).
  - roles.*: each element must exist as a role id (so roles is an array of role ids).
- The controller uses only the input fields name, email, password for the user update, and separately reads roles (array) to sync role IDs.
- Based on this, the parameters for the PATCH endpoint are:
  1) A path parameter "user" (integer, required).
  2) A body parameter (named "user") with schema object containing properties name, email, password, password_confirmation, roles (array of integers). The UsersRequest enforces name and email as required.

